    Date: Wed, 18 Nov 87 14:52:01 -0500
    From: Craig Partridge &lt;craig@NNSC.NSF.NET&gt;


    &gt; Turning the tables, do you agree that my scheme can also work?

    No, I'm afraid I don't believe your scheme can work without both:

	(1) The addition of a site indicator to every mail record.

I don't understand this.  What's a "mail record"?  Where do they appear
such that I need a site attached to "every" one of them?  My proposal
was that if, in the mailbox@maildrop syntax, 
 - If maildrop is a host, you look up the site of the host and then ask
   the site for maildelivery information.
 - If maildrop is a site, you ask the site for maildelivery information. 

	(2) A good definition of site.

I have a pretty good one.  It is much different than yours.  It is much
closer to the Symbolics namespace system's concept of a site.  Roughly,
a site is a related group of machines.  It is usually a subgroup within
a larger organization, but needn't be.  A better definition will appear
in a set of RFCs I and others hope to write.

Sites are not MD or MF records, and in the naming scheme I would like to
see exist, there is no such thing as related data timing out at
different times.  This is because there is no such thing as
timeout=destroy, and I think that is one of the big failings of the
domain system.  timeout should equal stale, and the stale data should
be allowed to be (nonauthoritatively) used until proven otherwise.

    Happy to be proved wrong.

Does the above help?

